13 Nonlinear Classification Models

This is a tidymodels implementation of the code in Chapter 13 of Applied Predictive Modeling by Max Kuhn and Kjell Johnson1.

The authors use the Kaggle grant data set to demonstrate the models. I have chosen to demonstrate each model on a different data set in this notebook. The data set I have used is the Credit Approval Data Set which is available at the UCI Machine Learning Repository2. This data set is moderate in size (\(n = 653\), \(p = 16\)). It has a binary outcome variable which is relatively balanced. There is a mixture of categorical and numeric predictors, and only a small amount of missing data.

Each model is implemented in its own section, including preprocessing and tuning. The models are then collectively assessed in the Metrics section, which includes ROC curves and lift/gain charts for each model.

# Prepare data:
df <- read_csv("/home/brian/R/dir/APM/chapter12/data/crx.data", col_names = F, na = '?') %>% 
  mutate(y = factor(X16),
         X11 = parse_number(X11),     # this should be continuous according to the description
         X14 = parse_number(X14)) %>% # this should be continuous according to the description
  # Using '+' and '-' causes problems for R so switch to simple strings;
  mutate(y = factor(if_else(y == "+", "yes", "no"), levels = c("yes", "no"))) %>% 
  # drop the original response, X16;
  dplyr::select(y, everything(), -X16)

13.1 Nonlinear Discriminant Analysis

Mixture Discriminant Analysis

There is no MDA implementation in tidymodels as yet.

Quadratic Discriminant Analysis

QDA is a special case of regularized discriminant analysis.

To implement QDA the function discrim_regularized() is used with the frac_common_cov parameter set to 0. A value of 1 for this parameter is equivalent to LDA, and zero means there are fully separate covariance matrices for each class, which is the definition of QDA.

No resampling is used. I will fit() a model on the training data and make predictions on the test data.

Training data

# Preprocessing
rec1 <-
  recipe(y ~ ., data = df_train) %>% 
  step_center(all_numeric()) %>% 
  step_scale(all_numeric()) %>% 
  step_nzv(all_predictors()) %>% 
  step_corr(all_numeric(), threshold = 0.9) %>% 
  step_dummy(all_nominal(), -all_outcomes())

# Model
qda_mod <-
  discrim_regularized(frac_common_cov = 0) %>% 
  set_mode("classification") %>% 
  set_engine("klaR") # this engine is required here

# Workflow
workflow <- 
  workflow() %>% 
  add_recipe(rec1) %>% 
  add_model(spec = qda_mod)

# Fit
qda_fit <- 
  workflow %>% 
  fit(data = df_train)

# View fit:
qda_fit %>% 
  pull_workflow_fit()

Regularized LDA

This model is implemented by using the parameters frac_common_cov and frac_identity in the discrim_regularized() function. We will use cross-validation to tune the parameters.

For preprocessing, I will remove NZV variables and highly correlated variables. I will also center and scale the variables.

Training data

# Preprocessing
rec1 <-   
  recipe(y ~ ., data = df_train) %>% 
  step_center(all_numeric()) %>% 
  step_scale(all_numeric()) %>% 
  step_nzv(all_predictors()) %>% 
  step_corr(all_numeric(), threshold = 0.9) %>% 
  step_dummy(all_nominal(), -all_outcomes())

# Model
regularized_lda_mod1 <-
  discrim_regularized(frac_common_cov = tune(), frac_identity = tune()) %>% 
  set_mode("classification") %>% 
  set_engine("klaR")

# Tuning grid
grid1 <- grid_regular(list(frac_common_cov = frac_common_cov(), frac_identity = frac_identity()), levels = 10)

# Workflow
workflow <- 
  workflow() %>% 
  add_model(spec = regularized_lda_mod1) %>% 
  add_recipe(rec1)

# Tune
### Read in cached results if available:
file1 <- "/home/brian/R/dir/APM/chapter13/objects/regularized_lda_res1_clean.RDS"
if (file.exists(file1)) {
  regularized_lda_res1 <- readRDS(file1)
} else {
  regularized_lda_res1 <- 
    workflow %>% 
    tune_grid(resamples = folds, grid = grid1)
  saveRDS(regularized_lda_res1, file1)
}

# Plot AUC:
## Line plot:
p1 <- autoplot(regularized_lda_res1, metric = "roc_auc") +
  ggsci::scale_color_d3() +
  labs(color = "Fraction of the\nIdentity Matrix") +
  theme(legend.position = "top",
        legend.title = element_text(size = 10)) +
  ggtitle("Line plot of RDA tuning profile")

## Tile plot like Fig. 12.16:
p2 <- regularized_lda_res1 %>% 
  collect_metrics() %>% 
  filter(.metric == "roc_auc") %>% 
  ggplot() +
  geom_tile(aes(frac_common_cov, frac_identity, fill = mean)) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 1, 0.25)) +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 1, 0.25)) +
  scale_fill_viridis_c() + # it looks better with the default direction
  coord_cartesian(expand = F) +
  labs(x = "Fraction of the Common Covariance Matrix", y = "Fraction of the Identity Matrix", fill = "AUC",
       title = "Tile plot of RDA tuning profile") +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

cowplot::plot_grid(plotlist = list(p1, p2), nrow = 1, rel_widths = c(5.5, 4.5))

Test data

best_mod <- regularized_lda_res1 %>%
  select_best("roc_auc")

# Update final workflow:
final_wf <- 
  workflow %>% 
  finalize_workflow(best_mod)

# Fit final model and make predictions:
final_fit <- 
  final_wf %>%
  last_fit(splits)

# Collect predictions:

    test_results,
    cbind(
      final_fit %>%
        collect_predictions(),
      model = "Regularized LDA"

Training data

  step_center(all_numeric()) %>%

grid1 <- expand.grid(hidden_units = 1:10, penalty = c(0, 0.1, 1, 2))

    workflow %>%

13.3 Flexible Discriminant Analysis

FDA is implemented using the discrim_flexible() function in the discrim package. I will tune a FDA model using the same grid as with the caret model, except that I will tune over values of one and two for the degree (prod_degree).

Training data

# Preprocessing
rec1 <-   
  recipe(y ~ ., data = df_train) %>% 
  step_center(all_numeric()) %>% 
  step_scale(all_numeric()) %>% 
  step_nzv(all_predictors()) %>% 
  step_corr(all_numeric(), threshold = 0.9) %>% 
  step_dummy(all_nominal(), -all_outcomes())

# Model
fda_mod1 <-
  discrim_flexible(num_terms = tune(), prod_degree = tune()) %>% 
  set_mode("classification") %>% 
  set_engine("earth")

# Tuning grid
grid1 <- expand.grid(prod_degree = 1:2, num_terms = 2:25)

# Workflow
workflow <- 
  workflow() %>% 
  add_model(spec = fda_mod1) %>% 
  add_recipe(rec1)

# Tune
### Read in cached results if available:

if (file.exists(file1)) {
  fda_res1 <- readRDS(file1)

  fda_res1 <- 
    workflow %>% 
    tune_grid(resamples = folds, grid = grid1)

# Plot AUC:

Metrics

Calculate metrics

get_metrics <- function(test_results, model) {
  test_results <- test_results %>% 
    filter(model == {{ model }})
  
  metrics <- caret::confusionMatrix(data = test_results$.pred_class,
                                    reference = test_results$y,
                                    positive = "yes")
  
  metrics$auc <- 
    test_results %>% 
    yardstick::roc_auc(y, .pred_yes, event_level = "first") %>% # *1
    pluck(".estimate")
  
  return(metrics)
}

models <- unique(test_results$model)
metrics <- map(models, ~get_metrics(test_results, .x)) %>% 
  set_names(models)

# *1: event_level not required but added for clarity. It refers to the first level in the levels of the response. Since "yes" is the target and the first level, I have set those arguments here. It was different for the churn model in APM_12_exercise_12.3.Rmd because "yes" was the second level but the important thing is to be consistent. Same thing with the ROC curves and lift/gain charts below.

# Display a named list of metrics as a table as opposed to a vector:
bh_display_metric <- function(metrics, type = "Metric") { # metrics is a named vector of doubles
  M <- matrix(metrics)
  dimnames(M) <- list(names(metrics), type)
  return(M)
}

ROC Curves

# Returns an ROC curve for a given model:
plot_roc_curve <- function(test_results, model) {
  
  # Get AUC for labeling the plot:
  auc <- metrics[[{{ model }}]]$auc

  # ROC curve:
  p <- test_results %>% 
    filter(model == {{ model }}) %>% 
    yardstick::roc_curve(y, .pred_yes, event_level = "first") %>% 
    autoplot() +
    geom_label(aes(x = 0.75, y = 0.25, label = paste0("AUC:", round(auc, 3)))) +
    ggtitle(paste0("ROC - ", {{ model }}))
  return(p)
}

cowplot::plot_grid(
  plotlist = map(models, ~plot_roc_curve(test_results, .x))
)

Gain Curves

# Returns a gain curve for a given model:
plot_gain_curve <- function(test_results, model) {
  
  # Gain curve:
  p <- test_results %>% 
    filter(model == {{ model }}) %>% 
    yardstick::gain_curve(y, .pred_yes, event_level = "first") %>% 
    autoplot() +
    ggtitle(paste0("Gain - ", {{ model }}))
  return(p)
}

cowplot::plot_grid(
  plotlist = map(models, ~plot_gain_curve(test_results, .x))
)
